Edo State government has declared zero tolerance for Lassa fever. It urged health officials in the 18 local government areas to ensure it is contained. Commissioner for Communication and Orientatio, Andrew Emwanta, who addressed reporters after the State Executive Council SEC) meeting yesterday, said Governor Godwin Obaseki also approved the relocation of the Civil Service Recreation Centre on Osadebe Avenue, GRA, to a more suitable location. He said: “According to the Commissioner for Health, Prof. Akoria Obehi, who is also a member of the state’s taskforce on Lassa fever, the state has not had any new case. The council has resolved that environmental health officers in the local government areas, especially those in the affected areas, will be held responsible for any new outbreak.   Peter Obi laments killings in Southeast     As Nigeria celebrates Children’s Day     Issues in the proposed IHR amendment   “The council also decided that the Civil Service Recreation Centre at Osadebe Avenue in GRA should be relocated to a more suitable premises at Oguola Crescent. This is because the present location is a residential area, and the new area should be more suitable for that particular purpose. The exco approved the acquisition of new premises at Oguola Crescent.” Commissioner for Agriculture and Food Security Stephen Idehenre said the firms that were allocated land by the government for oil palm production had started developing their lands, noting that land preparation and nursery development were in top gear. He noted that the firms were currently engaging with their host communities. “Mr. Governor urges these communities to cooperate with the investors as it will help the state in terms of economic development.”